 is universality attained not by the sword, but by the force of brotherhood and of our brotherly striving toward the reunification of mankind." This is the Dostoevsky who has entered the patrimony of world literature, though he was not always capable of living up to such exalted ideals. The writer's death in St. Petersburg in January of 1881 concludes this unparalleled literary biography--one truly worthy of Dostoevsky's genius and of the remarkable time and place in which he lived.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aNovelists, Russiany19th centuryvBiography. 4aAnna Karenina. 4aCatechism of a Revolutionary. 4aChildhood and Boyhood. 4aCrisis in Western Philosophy. 4aDavid Copperfield. 4aDowntrodden People. 4aEpoch. 4aEvgeny Onegin. 4aLife of a Great Sinner. 4aLittle Hero. 4aMimochka. 4aPetersburg Almanac. 4aRaw Youth. 4aSkladchina. 4aThe Brothers Karamazov. 4aThe Dream of a Ridiculous Man. 4aThe Eternal Husband. 4aThe Landlady. 4aThe Old Curiosity Shop. 4aThe Queen of Spades. 4aThe Tale of the Bear. 4aanti-Semitism. 4aatheism. 4anarodnichestvo. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691209364423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691209364.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK